SECTION 3. FINDINGS.
================================================================================

Congress finds the following:

--- Constitutional Basis ---

(1) The Constitution of the United States vests in Congress, under Article I,
Section 8, the power to regulate commerce with foreign nations, to define and
punish offenses against the law of nations, to declare war, to raise and
support armies, to maintain a navy, and to make all laws necessary and proper
for carrying these powers into execution. These powers exist for the security
and welfare of the American people, not for the perpetuation of any particular
monetary arrangement, military posture, or pattern of international economic
extraction.

(2) Article II, Section 2 of the Constitution grants the President the power
to make treaties with the advice and consent of the Senate. The alliance
commitments addressed by this Act derive their legitimacy from that provision,
and their renegotiation is equally within the constitutional authority of the
federal government to pursue.

(3) The Supremacy Clause of Article VI establishes that treaties made under
the authority of the United States are the supreme law of the land. This Act
does not abrogate existing treaty obligations unilaterally; it directs the
Executive Branch to pursue their renegotiation through lawful diplomatic
processes, consistent with the terms of each treaty and with the evolving
security requirements of the United States and its allies.

(4) The Tenth Amendment reserves to the states and to the people powers not
delegated to the federal government. The principle of subsidiarity that
underlies this reservation -- that governance is most legitimate when exercised
at the scale closest to the people it serves -- applies with equal force to
the international order. A world in which communities govern their own land,
knowledge, data, and productive enterprise through federated commons
institutions is more consistent with the constitutional vision of self-
governance than a world organized around the dominance of any single nation,
monetary system, or multilateral institution.

--- The Alliance Transition Already Underway ---

(5) The international security architecture established following the Second
World War, and substantially reorganized following the conclusion of the Cold
War, was premised on a degree of American military and economic primacy that
the intervening decades have progressively eroded. The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization, conceived as a collective defense arrangement among sovereign
equals, has functioned in practice as a security guarantee underwritten by
American military expenditure, American nuclear deterrence, and American
willingness to treat the defense of allied territory as equivalent to the
defense of American territory. That arrangement served identifiable purposes
during the period of its design. It is not self-evidently the arrangement best
suited to the security requirements of the present moment or the coming
decades.

(6) The process of European strategic reorientation is not a future possibility
requiring American initiation; it is a present reality requiring American
governance. The 2026 National Defense Strategy's explicit deprioritization of
Europe as a conventional defense theater, the Northwood Declaration's
coordination of Anglo-French nuclear policy, the European Union's Defense
Readiness Roadmap 2030, and the commitment of all NATO allies at the 2025
Hague Summit to defense expenditure targets substantially exceeding prior
benchmarks collectively demonstrate that European allies have already concluded
that automatic American primacy cannot be assumed indefinitely. The question
before Congress is not whether this transition will occur but whether the
United States will govern it deliberately, in ways consistent with the commons
values of this legislative program, or allow it to proceed as an unmanaged
fracture driven by transactional American politics and European rearmament
anxiety.

(7) The fracture of the NATO alliance over American demands for allied
participation in operations connected to the Strait of Hormuz illustrates with
particular clarity the structural problem this Act is designed to address.
American military commitments to the protection of fossil fuel shipping lanes
are not mutual security commitments in any meaningful sense; they are the
operational expression of petrodollar dependence, requiring allied nations to
subordinate their own security assessments to the protection of an American
monetary arrangement whose benefits they do not share equally and whose
continuation they have no independent interest in guaranteeing. As the domestic
commons infrastructure established by the Federal Resilience and
Decentralization Initiatives Act reduces American dependence on fossil fuel
markets, the strategic rationale for those commitments diminishes
correspondingly, and the alliance relationships they have strained can be
rebuilt on more genuinely mutual foundations.

(8) The European defense buildup now underway represents a resource
mobilization of historic scale. Analyses conducted by the International
Institute for Strategic Studies and comparable bodies estimate the cost of
replacing American conventional defense capabilities in Europe at figures
exceeding one trillion dollars over a generation. That mobilization will occur
regardless of American policy choices. The question is whether it occurs as
conventional military rearmament reproducing the same extractive defense
industrial logic at European scale, or as resilience-based security investment
in distributed energy infrastructure, cooperative food systems, democratic
communications architecture, and the commons institutions that constitute
genuine civilian resilience. This Act directs American diplomacy toward
supporting the latter.

(9) Congress finds that the current trajectory of American alliance management,
characterized by transactional conditionality, public questioning of Article 5
commitments, and the subordination of alliance relationships to domestic
political signaling, inflicts costs on American security that no short-term
diplomatic leverage justifies. The credibility of security commitments derives
from their unconditional character; a commitment that is conditional on allied
deference to American economic preferences is not a security commitment but a
protection arrangement, and its erosion produces not leverage but insecurity.
This Act does not diminish American security commitments. It places them on
foundations -- mutual resilience, genuine collective defense, commons
solidarity -- that are more durable than the petrodollar arrangements whose
protection has distorted them.

--- Nuclear Nonproliferation and the Broader Logic ---

(10) The Treaty on the Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons, to which the
United States is a party, commits nuclear-weapon states to pursue negotiations
in good faith toward nuclear disarmament. That commitment has been honored
rhetorically and neglected practically for more than five decades. The
proliferation of nuclear weapons to additional states, and the erosion of the
nonproliferation regime through the withdrawal of parties and the collapse of
bilateral arms control agreements, represents a security failure whose costs
will ultimately be borne by the communities whose commons infrastructure this
legislative program is designed to protect. This Act directs a genuine
reengagement with multilateral disarmament processes, from a posture of minimum
credible deterrence that does not require the forward deployment of nuclear
capabilities whose primary strategic purpose is the coercion of non-nuclear
states.

(11) The logic of nonproliferation extends beyond nuclear weapons to encompass
the full range of arrangements whose proliferation produces insecurity,
ecological harm, and the concentration of productive capacity in forms
incompatible with commons governance. The proliferation of fossil fuel
infrastructure, whose continued expansion is incompatible with the ecological
stability on which all commons governance ultimately depends; the proliferation
of surveillance and carceral technology, whose export by American and allied
governments has systematically undermined the conditions for commons institution
development abroad; the proliferation of extractive financial arrangements,
whose structural adjustment conditions have prevented developing nations from
building the cooperative institutions that this legislative program establishes
domestically: each of these represents a form of proliferation whose deliberate
non-proliferation is as much a security imperative as the control of nuclear
weapons. This Act encodes that broader nonproliferation logic in the direction
it gives to American diplomacy, without requiring any single provision to carry
the full weight of the argument.

(12) The ecological disruption produced by the combustion of fossil fuels
constitutes a security threat of the first order, generating the displacement
of human populations, the destabilization of agricultural systems, the
intensification of resource conflicts, and the erosion of the material
conditions on which all governance -- commons or otherwise -- depends. A
foreign policy that continues to prioritize the protection of fossil fuel
infrastructure and the perpetuation of dollar-denominated energy markets is a
foreign policy that actively accelerates the security threats it purports to
address. This Act redirects American international engagement toward the
conditions for ecological stability, including through support for commons
institution development in nations most vulnerable to climate disruption, whose
institutions may in time federate laterally with the United States Federated
Network and with one another across borders and oceans, governed by shared
principles rather than by any hierarchical relationship to any center.

(13) Congress finds that the four legislative vehicles constituting this
program -- the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act, the
Human Reclamation and Community Restorative Act, the Federal Commons Security
and Automation Governance Act, and this Act -- together constitute a complete
transition architecture: from an economy organized around scarcity, enclosure,
and extraction to one organized around abundance, commons stewardship, and
provision; from a justice system organized around punishment to one organized
around restoration; from a defense posture organized around power projection
to one organized around resilience; and from an international order organized
around the dominance of any single nation or monetary system to one organized
around the federated sovereignty of communities governing their own land,
knowledge, data, and productive enterprise. This Act is the capstone of that
architecture, addressing the international dimensions of a transition whose
domestic foundations the preceding Acts have established.

--- This Act Does Not Create a New System ---

(14) The international commons institutions whose recognition, connection, and
capitalization this Act provides already exist and already function. The
international community land trust movement, the Mondragon cooperative
federation's international network, the Barcelona en Comu municipal commons
network and the broader fearless cities movement, the solidarity economy
networks of Catalonia and the Basque Country, and the mutual credit and
time-banking systems operating in the Global South represent an existing
institutional infrastructure whose demonstrated effectiveness justifies the
diplomatic recognition and material support this Act provides. These
institutions are not recipients of American development assistance in the
conventional sense. They are potential equals in a planetary commons network:
each self-governing under principles equivalent to the Ostrom Standards of
Stewardship, each federated laterally to its neighbors and to the United States
Federated Network, none subordinate to any center. The commons federation this
Act enables has no metropole. It has only nodes, each sovereign, each
provisioning its members, each connected to every other through the same
governance logic that makes the domestic Federated Network resilient. This Act
removes the legal and diplomatic barriers that keep these institutions fragmented
and provides the framework for their recognition as legitimate governance
institutions in the international order.

(15) The renegotiation of alliance commitments directed by this Act does not
begin from a blank slate. Existing NATO structures, bilateral security
agreements, and multilateral institution memberships provide the legal and
institutional foundation on which renegotiation proceeds. The direction this
Act gives to American diplomacy is not the abandonment of international
engagement but its reorientation: from arrangements organized around American
primacy and petrodollar protection to arrangements organized around mutual
resilience, commons solidarity, and the deliberate non-proliferation of the
extractive systems whose continuation no community, American or otherwise, has
a genuine interest in guaranteeing.

--- The Planetary Commons Federation ---

(16) The planetary commons federation this Act encodes in legal architecture
is the structural inverse of empire. Empire extracts: it takes land, labor,
knowledge, and resources from the periphery and concentrates them at the
center, maintaining that concentration through military projection, monetary
dominance, and the enclosure of the intellectual and material commons. The
commons federation this Act enables distributes: it seeds self-governing
institutions at every node of the network, connects them laterally through
shared governance principles and mutual provision obligations, and actively
reverses the extraction dynamic by returning to communities the productive
capacity, the knowledge commons, and the land stewardship that prior
arrangements removed. The United States has, through the mechanisms this
program dismantles, been the primary institutional author of the conditions
that prevent commons governance from taking root in the nations most in need
of it. This Act does not merely stop doing those things. It runs the process
in the opposite direction, using the diplomatic, financial, and institutional
capacity of the federal government not to project American power but to seed
the conditions under which no projection of power, American or otherwise, is
any longer necessary or possible.


