SECTION 4. DEFINITIONS.
================================================================================

In this Act:

(1) ALLIED COMMONS NETWORK.-- The term "Allied Commons Network" means a
foreign commons institution, federation of commons institutions, or municipal
commons governance body that has been formally recognized pursuant to Section
401 of Title IV of this Act as operating under governance principles equivalent
to the Ostrom Standards of Stewardship, and that has entered into a Commons
Federation Agreement with one or more Qualified Federated Networks pursuant
to Section 402 of Title IV of this Act. Recognition as an Allied Commons
Network does not require that the foreign institution meet every certification
requirement applicable to a Qualified Federated Cooperative or Qualified
Federated Network under the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives
Act; it requires only that the institution demonstrate governance principles
substantively equivalent to the Ostrom Standards of Stewardship and a
commitment to the commons values of this legislative program. The benefit of
full QFN certification, for domestic and foreign institutions alike, is access
to the broader interoperable commons infrastructure; recognition as an Allied
Commons Network is the pathway by which foreign institutions enter that
pipeline on terms appropriate to their own legal, cultural, and institutional
contexts.

(2) COMMONS FEDERATION AGREEMENT.-- The term "Commons Federation Agreement"
means a bilateral or multilateral agreement negotiated pursuant to Section 402
of Title IV of this Act between the United States and one or more foreign
governments or international commons networks, providing for mutual recognition
of commons membership, inter-commons intellectual property sharing, inter-
commons data governance, and commons-to-commons resource exchange, on terms
consistent with the commons values of the Federal Resilience and
Decentralization Initiatives Act.

(3) EXTRACTIVE STRUCTURAL CONDITION.-- The term "Extractive Structural
Condition" means any condition, requirement, or policy prescription attached
by the International Monetary Fund, the World Bank, the World Trade
Organization, or any other multilateral economic institution to the provision
of financing, debt relief, trade access, or technical assistance, that requires
a recipient nation to: privatize publicly or cooperatively held assets;
liberalize capital flows in ways that expose domestic commons institutions to
speculative acquisition; reduce public expenditure on housing, nutrition,
healthcare, or education below the level necessary to maintain a provision
standard equivalent to the Guaranteed Provision Standard; extend intellectual
property protections beyond what is necessary to fulfill treaty obligations
under the Agreement on Trade-Related Aspects of Intellectual Property Rights;
or otherwise adopt economic arrangements incompatible with the development of
commons institutions as defined under the Federal Resilience and
Decentralization Initiatives Act.

(4) GUARANTEED PROVISION STANDARD.-- The term "Guaranteed Provision Standard"
has the meaning given such term in Section 4(10) of the Federal Resilience and
Decentralization Initiatives Act.

(5) INTERNATIONAL COMMONS SOLIDARITY FUND.-- The term "International Commons
Solidarity Fund" means the fund established under Section 403 of Title IV of
this Act to provide technical assistance, open-source technology transfer,
commons governance capacity-building support, and seed capitalization to
commons institutions in nations seeking to develop federated commons
infrastructure, funded through the mechanisms established in Section 1005(e)
of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act and supplemented
by the appropriations authorized under Title V of this Act.

(6) MINIMUM CREDIBLE DETERRENCE.-- The term "Minimum Credible Deterrence"
means a nuclear posture providing the United States with the capability to
inflict unacceptable costs on any state actor that conducts a nuclear first
strike against the United States or its Treaty Allies, through a force
structure limited to what is necessary for that specific deterrent purpose
and not sized or deployed for the purpose of nuclear coercion of non-nuclear
states, first-strike capability against nuclear-armed adversaries, or the
reinforcement of conventional military dominance through nuclear threat.

(7) MUTUAL RESILIENCE COMMITMENT.-- The term "Mutual Resilience Commitment"
means a security commitment between the United States and an allied nation or
Allied Commons Network that encompasses not only the conventional collective
defense obligations of existing treaty arrangements but also mutual obligations
of commons infrastructure protection, democratic governance resilience, and
economic sovereignty, treating attacks on a partner's energy commons, food
commons, data commons, or democratic institutions as security matters of
equivalent gravity to conventional military attack.

(8) NATO RESILIENCE FRAMEWORK.-- The term "NATO Resilience Framework" means
the renegotiated framework for United States participation in the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization established pursuant to Title I of this Act,
under which American commitments are reoriented from automatic conventional
primacy toward Mutual Resilience Commitments, burden-sharing is assessed
against commons infrastructure investment as well as conventional defense
expenditure, and alliance governance reflects the genuine equality of sovereign
member states rather than the subordination of allied security assessments to
American monetary and energy interests.

(9) NONPROLIFERATION LOGIC.-- The term "Nonproliferation Logic" means the
governing principle, established in Finding 11 of Section 3 of this Act, that
the deliberate non-proliferation of arrangements whose proliferation produces
insecurity, ecological harm, or the concentration of productive capacity in
forms incompatible with commons governance -- including fossil fuel
infrastructure, surveillance and carceral technology, and extractive financial
arrangements -- is a security imperative of equivalent standing to the control
of nuclear weapons, and that American foreign policy shall be directed
accordingly.

(10) OSTROM STANDARDS OF STEWARDSHIP.-- The term "Ostrom Standards of
Stewardship" has the meaning given such term in Section 4(16) of the Federal
Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act.

(11) QUALIFIED FEDERATED NETWORK or QFN.-- The term "Qualified Federated
Network" has the meaning given such term in Section 4(20) of the Federal
Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act.

(12) RESILIENCE-BASED DEFENSE POSTURE.-- The term "Resilience-Based Defense
Posture" has the meaning given such term in Section 4(15) of the Federal
Commons Security and Automation Governance Act.

(13) STRUCTURAL ADJUSTMENT REFORM DIRECTIVE.-- The term "Structural Adjustment
Reform Directive" means a formal instruction issued by the United States
Executive Director at the International Monetary Fund, the World Bank, or any
other multilateral economic institution pursuant to Section 302 of Title III
of this Act, directing that institution to modify, withdraw, or refrain from
imposing any Extractive Structural Condition in connection with any financing,
debt relief, trade access, or technical assistance arrangement with any member
nation.

(14) TREATY ALLY.-- The term "Treaty Ally" means any nation with which the
United States maintains a mutual defense treaty obligation as of the date of
enactment of this Act, including all member states of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization and all nations party to bilateral mutual defense treaties with
the United States.


================================================================================
TITLE I -- NATO AND ALLIANCE GOVERNANCE
================================================================================

The purpose of this Title is to establish the legal architecture through which
the United States governs its transition from a posture of automatic
conventional primacy within the North Atlantic Treaty Organization and related
security arrangements to a posture of genuine collective defense grounded in
Mutual Resilience Commitments among sovereign equals. This Title does not
abrogate Article 5 of the North Atlantic Treaty or any other mutual defense
obligation of the United States. It strengthens those obligations by placing
them on foundations more durable than the petrodollar arrangements whose
protection has distorted them, and by directing the renegotiation of alliance
governance toward a NATO Resilience Framework in which burden-sharing reflects
investment in commons infrastructure and civilian resilience as well as
conventional military expenditure. The transition this Title governs is already
underway; the question this Title answers is whether it proceeds as a managed
reorientation serving the genuine security interests of all allied nations or
as an unmanaged fracture serving none of them. Nothing in this Title shall be
construed to reduce the readiness or capability of the United States Armed
Forces to fulfill any mutual defense commitment to any Treaty Ally.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 101. DECLARATION OF ALLIANCE GOVERNANCE POLICY.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) DECLARATION.-- It is hereby declared to be the policy of the United States
that:

    (1) the collective defense commitments of the North Atlantic Treaty,
    including the mutual defense obligation of Article 5, remain binding,
    unconditional, and fully supported by the United States, and that no
    transactional conditionality, burden-sharing dispute, or bilateral
    disagreement shall be permitted to qualify or undermine the credibility
    of those commitments;

    (2) the governance of the NATO alliance shall reflect the genuine equality
    of sovereign member states, with American participation grounded in mutual
    security rather than in the maintenance of American conventional primacy
    or the protection of dollar-denominated energy markets;

    (3) burden-sharing assessments within NATO shall account for investment
    in commons infrastructure, distributed renewable energy capacity,
    cooperative food systems, and civilian resilience architecture as
    contributions to collective security of equivalent standing to conventional
    defense expenditure, recognizing that a nation whose communities can
    provision themselves through resilient, locally governed infrastructure
    is a more secure ally than one dependent on centralized corporate supply
    chains vulnerable to disruption;

    (4) the European defense buildup currently underway shall be directed,
    through American diplomatic engagement pursuant to this Title, toward
    resilience-based security investment rather than toward conventional
    military rearmament that reproduces the extractive defense industrial
    logic this legislative program is designed to replace; and

    (5) the United States shall pursue the negotiation of a NATO Resilience
    Framework, as defined in Section 4(8) of this Act, through the consultative
    processes of the alliance, treating that negotiation as an expression of
    commitment to the alliance's long-term viability rather than as a threat
    to withdraw from it.

(b) PROHIBITION ON UNILATERAL WITHDRAWAL.-- Nothing in this Act shall be
construed to authorize or direct the unilateral withdrawal of the United States
from the North Atlantic Treaty or from any bilateral mutual defense treaty with
any Treaty Ally. The renegotiation directed by this Title proceeds within and
through existing alliance structures, not outside or against them. Any
modification of existing treaty obligations shall require the advice and consent
of the Senate pursuant to Article II, Section 2 of the Constitution.

(c) CONGRESSIONAL POLICY ON TRANSACTIONAL CONDITIONALITY.-- It is the policy
of Congress that the credibility of American mutual defense commitments derives
from their unconditional character, and that the following conduct by officers
of the Executive Branch is inconsistent with that policy and with the alliance
governance declaration of subsection (a) of this Section:

    (1) publicly questioning the unconditional character of any Article 5
    commitment or any bilateral mutual defense treaty obligation of the United
    States as a means of extracting allied compliance with any American economic,
    military, or political demand;

    (2) conditioning any security commitment, intelligence sharing arrangement,
    or defense cooperation agreement with any Treaty Ally on that ally's support
    for American operations whose primary purpose is the protection of fossil
    fuel infrastructure or the maintenance of petrodollar arrangements; or

    (3) using any security commitment of the United States as leverage in any
    trade, monetary, or commercial negotiation with any Treaty Ally.

    Any officer of the Executive Branch whose conduct is found by the
    congressional oversight process of Section 104 of this Title to be
    inconsistent with this policy shall be subject to referral for appropriate
    congressional action, including referral to the relevant Senate confirmation
    committee for reconsideration of confirmation status where applicable, and
    referral to the House Committee on the Judiciary for consideration of whether
    the conduct constitutes grounds for impeachment proceedings. Nothing in this
    subsection shall be construed to abrogate any constitutional right of any
    officer or employee of the Executive Branch, or to restrict the President's
    authority to conduct foreign affairs; it states the policy of Congress and
    establishes the oversight framework through which that policy is enforced.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 102. THE NATO RESILIENCE FRAMEWORK -- NEGOTIATING DIRECTIVE.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) DIRECTIVE.-- The President, acting through the Secretary of State and the
United States Permanent Representative to NATO, is hereby directed to pursue
the negotiation of a NATO Resilience Framework with all member states of the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization. The negotiation shall be conducted through
the alliance's existing consultative structures, shall treat all member states
as sovereign equals in the process, and shall proceed on the following
principles:

    (1) EXPANDED COLLECTIVE DEFENSE SCOPE.-- The NATO Resilience Framework
    shall expand the scope of collective defense beyond conventional military
    attack to encompass Mutual Resilience Commitments, including attacks on
    energy commons, food commons, data commons, communications infrastructure,
    and democratic governance institutions, treating hybrid warfare, cyberattack,
    and infrastructure sabotage as triggering collective defense obligations
    equivalent in gravity to conventional military attack;

    (2) RESILIENCE-BASED BURDEN SHARING.-- The NATO Resilience Framework shall
    establish a burden-sharing assessment methodology that credits member states
    for investment in commons infrastructure, distributed renewable energy
    capacity, cooperative food systems, open-source communications
    infrastructure, and civilian resilience architecture, in addition to
    conventional defense expenditure, with the specific weighting of each
    category determined through collective negotiation among member states;

    (3) COMMONS INFRASTRUCTURE MUTUAL SUPPORT.-- The NATO Resilience Framework
    shall establish mutual obligations among member states to support the
    development of commons infrastructure in member states whose resilience
    capacity is below a defined threshold, treating the resilience gap between
    the most and least resilient member states as a collective security
    vulnerability requiring collective investment;

    (4) FOSSIL FUEL MISSION EXCLUSION.-- The NATO Resilience Framework shall
    explicitly exclude the protection of fossil fuel extraction, processing,
    or distribution infrastructure owned or operated by private entities from
    the scope of collective defense obligations, consistent with the
    Resilience-Based Defense Posture established under the Federal Commons
    Security and Automation Governance Act; and

    (5) DEMOCRATIC GOVERNANCE AS MEMBERSHIP CONDITION.-- The NATO Resilience
    Framework shall reaffirm and strengthen the alliance's existing democratic
    governance membership conditions, providing that sustained and documented
    erosion of democratic institutions, judicial independence, or press freedom
    within a member state constitutes a collective security concern subject to
    alliance-level consultation and, where unremedied, to suspension of that
    member state's full participation in alliance governance.

(b) TIMELINE.-- The President shall:

    (1) submit to Congress, within one year of the date of enactment of this
    Act, a comprehensive negotiating strategy for the NATO Resilience Framework,
    developed in consultation with Treaty Allies and reflecting their input into
    the framework's design;

    (2) report to Congress not less than annually on the progress of NATO
    Resilience Framework negotiations, including the positions of individual
    member states, the areas of agreement and disagreement, and the projected
    timeline for conclusion; and

    (3) submit any concluded NATO Resilience Framework agreement to the Senate
    for its advice and consent pursuant to Article II, Section 2 of the
    Constitution, prior to its entry into force.

(c) INTERIM CONDUCT.-- During the period preceding the conclusion of NATO
Resilience Framework negotiations, the United States shall:

    (1) continue to fulfill all existing NATO collective defense obligations
    in full, without reduction or qualification;

    (2) advocate within existing NATO structures for the adoption of resilience-
    based burden-sharing assessments on an interim basis, pending formal
    framework conclusion; and

    (3) direct its contributions to NATO common-funded programs preferentially
    toward resilience infrastructure, civilian preparedness, and hybrid warfare
    defense rather than toward conventional force projection capabilities whose
    strategic rationale derives primarily from petrodollar protection.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 103. BILATERAL ALLIANCE REVIEW.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) COMPREHENSIVE REVIEW.-- Within one year of the date of enactment of this
Act, the Secretary of State, in coordination with the Secretary of Defense,
shall conduct a comprehensive review of all bilateral mutual defense treaties
and security cooperation agreements to which the United States is a party,
assessing each against the following criteria:

    (1) whether the treaty or agreement serves a genuine mutual security
    purpose consistent with the Resilience-Based Defense Posture, as distinct
    from the protection of fossil fuel infrastructure, dollar-denominated
    commodity markets, or the commercial interests of American or allied
    corporations;

    (2) whether the treaty or agreement includes or is capable of incorporating
    Mutual Resilience Commitments addressing hybrid warfare, cyberattack, and
    commons infrastructure threats;

    (3) whether the partner nation's governance meets the democratic governance
    standards that genuine mutual security relationships require, with particular
    attention to partners whose primary strategic significance to the United
    States derives from resource endowments rather than from genuine security
    relationships; and

    (4) whether the treaty or agreement imposes obligations on the United States
    that are disproportionate to the mutual security benefit provided, including
    obligations to defend territory whose strategic connection to American
    security is primarily a function of its proximity to fossil fuel reserves
    or shipping routes.

(b) REPORT AND RECOMMENDATIONS.-- The Secretary of State shall submit the
findings and recommendations of the review required by subsection (a) of this
Section to Congress within eighteen months of the date of enactment of this
Act. The report shall:

    (1) identify each bilateral treaty or agreement reviewed, with an assessment
    of its consistency with the criteria of subsection (a);

    (2) recommend, for each treaty or agreement found inconsistent with those
    criteria, the specific renegotiation, modification, or termination that
    would bring American alliance commitments into alignment with the
    Resilience-Based Defense Posture; and

    (3) identify opportunities to incorporate Mutual Resilience Commitments
    into existing bilateral frameworks through executive agreement, without
    requiring full treaty renegotiation, where the partner nation's governance
    and security relationship support such incorporation.

(c) GULF STATE RELATIONSHIPS.-- The review required by this Section shall give
particular attention to the security relationships between the United States
and nations of the Persian Gulf region whose strategic significance to the
United States derives primarily from their petroleum reserves and their role
in the petrodollar recycling system. The review shall assess the timeline and
conditions under which those relationships can be reoriented toward genuine
mutual security foundations as American fossil fuel dependence diminishes
through the domestic commons transition established by the Federal Resilience
and Decentralization Initiatives Act, and shall recommend the specific
diplomatic steps necessary to manage that reorientation without creating
regional security vacuums that would serve the interests of no party.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 104. OVERSIGHT AND ACCOUNTABILITY.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) CONGRESSIONAL NOTIFICATION.-- The President shall notify the congressional
foreign affairs and armed services committees within seventy-two hours of any
executive branch statement, action, or omission that qualifies, conditions, or
publicly questions any mutual defense commitment of the United States in a
manner inconsistent with the congressional policy of Section 101(c) of this
Title, with a specific explanation of the circumstances and the corrective
actions taken or planned. Such notification shall constitute the triggering
event for the referral process established in Section 101(c) of this Title.

(b) ANNUAL ALLIANCE POSTURE REPORT.-- The Secretary of State and the Secretary
of Defense shall jointly submit to Congress an annual Alliance Posture Report
covering:

    (1) the status of NATO Resilience Framework negotiations pursuant to
    Section 102 of this Title;

    (2) the status of bilateral alliance reviews pursuant to Section 103 of
    this Title;

    (3) an assessment of the consistency of American alliance conduct during
    the preceding year with the declaration of Section 101(a) of this Title
    and the congressional policy of Section 101(c); and

    (4) the specific commons infrastructure investments made by Treaty Allies
    during the preceding year that qualify for burden-sharing credit under
    the resilience-based assessment methodology, with an assessment of trends
    in allied resilience capacity.

(c) INDEPENDENT REVIEW.-- The Government Accountability Office shall conduct
a biennial independent review of American alliance conduct, assessing
compliance with the policy declarations and prohibitions of this Title and
reporting findings to Congress with recommendations for corrective action
where violations are identified.


================================================================================
TITLE II -- NUCLEAR NONPROLIFERATION POSTURE
================================================================================

The purpose of this Title is to establish Minimum Credible Deterrence as the
governing principle of United States nuclear force structure and deployment,
to direct genuine American reengagement with multilateral nuclear disarmament
processes under the Treaty on the Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons, and
to encode the Nonproliferation Logic established in Finding 11 of Section 3
of this Act as the governing framework for American arms control and
disarmament diplomacy. A nuclear posture calibrated to Minimum Credible
Deterrence is not a weaker posture than one sized for coercion and first-
strike capability; it is a more defensible posture, more consistent with
American treaty obligations, and less dependent on the forward deployments
whose costs the American people bear without commensurate security benefit.
The deliberate non-proliferation of arrangements whose proliferation generates
insecurity -- nuclear, ecological, financial, and technological -- is the
through-line of this Title and of the legislative program of which it is
a part.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 201. NUCLEAR POSTURE -- MINIMUM CREDIBLE DETERRENCE.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) DECLARATION.-- It is hereby declared to be the policy of the United States
that its nuclear force structure and deployment shall be governed by the
principle of Minimum Credible Deterrence, as defined in Section 4(6) of this
Act. Specifically:

    (1) the United States shall maintain nuclear forces sufficient to deter
    any nuclear first strike against the United States or its Treaty Allies
    by ensuring that any such strike would result in unacceptable costs to
    the attacking state;

    (2) the United States shall not size, deploy, or posture its nuclear
    forces for the purpose of nuclear coercion of non-nuclear states, for
    first-strike capability against nuclear-armed adversaries, or for the
    reinforcement of conventional military dominance through nuclear threat;

    (3) the United States shall conduct a Nuclear Posture Review within one
    year of the date of enactment of this Act, assessing its current nuclear
    force structure and deployment against the Minimum Credible Deterrence
    standard and identifying reductions, redeployments, and posture changes
    consistent with that standard; and

    (4) the savings realized through nuclear force reductions authorized by
    the Nuclear Posture Review shall be redirected, not less than fifty
    percent, to the Bootstrap Grant Program established under Section 106
    of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act and to
    the International Commons Solidarity Fund established under Section 403
    of Title IV of this Act, treating the conversion of nuclear expenditure
    into commons infrastructure investment as itself an act of
    nonproliferation.

(b) FORWARD DEPLOYMENT REVIEW.-- The Nuclear Posture Review required by
subsection (a)(3) of this Section shall specifically assess the strategic
rationale for each forward deployment of American nuclear weapons on the
territory of Treaty Allies, examining:

    (1) whether the deployment serves a genuine deterrence purpose that
    cannot be served by submarine-based or continental United States-based
    forces;

    (2) whether the deployment creates escalation risks that outweigh its
    deterrence benefits; and

    (3) whether the host nation's preference for continued deployment reflects
    genuine security assessment or political signaling, and whether
    alternatives consistent with Mutual Resilience Commitments could satisfy
    the underlying security need.

(c) NO-FIRST-USE POLICY.-- Congress finds, pursuant to its authority under
Article I, Section 8 of the Constitution to make rules for the government and
regulation of the land and naval forces, that the first use of nuclear weapons
against any non-nuclear-weapon state does not serve a mission within the scope
of the Minimum Credible Deterrence posture established by subsection (a) of this
Section, and that planning for or executing such first use is inconsistent with
the Resilience-Based Defense Posture declared in Section 101 of Title I of the
Federal Commons Security and Automation Governance Act. Accordingly:

    (1) no funds appropriated under this Act, or under any other Act making
    appropriations for the Department of Defense or the Department of Energy's
    National Nuclear Security Administration, shall be used to develop, maintain,
    exercise, or execute any operational plan for the first use of nuclear weapons
    against any state that does not itself possess nuclear weapons; this funding
    restriction applies to targeting plans, employment orders, strike packages,
    and any related planning document;

    (2) the President is requested to issue a declaratory no-first-use policy
    consistent with paragraph (1) of this subsection and to pursue the
    incorporation of equivalent no-first-use commitments into the NATO Resilience
    Framework negotiations directed by Section 102 of Title I of this Act; and

    (3) nothing in this subsection shall be construed to limit planning for the
    use of nuclear weapons in response to a nuclear first strike against the
    United States or any Treaty Ally, which planning is fully consistent with
    and required by the Minimum Credible Deterrence posture of subsection (a)
    of this Section.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 202. NPT REENGAGEMENT.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) DIRECTIVE.-- The President, acting through the Secretary of State, is
hereby directed to pursue genuine American reengagement with the multilateral
nuclear disarmament process under Article VI of the Treaty on the Non-
Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons, which commits all nuclear-weapon states
parties to pursue negotiations in good faith on effective measures relating
to cessation of the nuclear arms race at an early date and to nuclear
disarmament. This reengagement shall be:

    (1) SUBSTANTIVE.-- consisting of specific, verifiable proposals for
    multilateral arms reduction rather than rhetorical endorsement of
    disarmament as a long-term aspiration without near-term operational
    content;

    (2) MULTILATERAL.-- pursued through the existing NPT framework and
    through engagement with all nuclear-weapon states, including those
    not currently party to bilateral arms control agreements with the
    United States, recognizing that the nonproliferation regime's
    credibility depends on the demonstrated good faith of nuclear-weapon
    states toward their Article VI obligations; and

    (3) CONNECTED TO THE BROADER NONPROLIFERATION LOGIC.-- framed in
    American diplomacy as part of a comprehensive reorientation toward
    the deliberate non-proliferation of arrangements whose proliferation
    generates insecurity, consistent with Finding 11 of Section 3 of this
    Act, rather than as an isolated arms control initiative detached from
    the broader strategic reorientation this legislative program encodes.

(b) BILATERAL ARMS CONTROL.-- The President is directed to resume bilateral
arms control negotiations with the Russian Federation for a successor
agreement to the New Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty, and to pursue equivalent
bilateral or multilateral arms reduction arrangements with all other nuclear-
armed states, on the following terms:

    (1) any successor agreement shall require verified reductions in deployed
    strategic nuclear warheads below the levels established by New START,
    consistent with the Minimum Credible Deterrence standard of Section 201
    of this Title;

    (2) any successor agreement shall include provisions for the extension
    of arms control disciplines to tactical nuclear weapons, which are
    excluded from existing bilateral agreements and whose forward deployment
    creates the greatest escalation risk; and

    (3) the United States shall not condition the resumption of arms control
    negotiations on the resolution of unrelated bilateral disputes, treating
    nuclear risk reduction as a matter of sufficient independent urgency to
    proceed on its own track regardless of the state of the broader bilateral
    relationship.

(c) TREATY ON THE PROHIBITION OF NUCLEAR WEAPONS.-- The President is directed
to engage constructively with the Treaty on the Prohibition of Nuclear Weapons
as an expression of the international security community's interests, without
being bound by its provisions during the transition to Minimum Credible
Deterrence, and to treat its entry into force among non-nuclear states as a
diplomatic asset rather than a diplomatic irritant, recognizing that the
delegitimization of nuclear weapons as instruments of policy serves American
security interests in a world where the United States no longer depends on
nuclear coercion to protect petrodollar arrangements.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 203. THE NONPROLIFERATION LOGIC -- ARMS CONTROL AND DISARMAMENT DIPLOMACY.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) GOVERNING PRINCIPLE.-- American arms control and disarmament diplomacy
shall be governed by the Nonproliferation Logic established in Section 4(9)
of this Act: the deliberate non-proliferation of arrangements whose
proliferation produces insecurity, ecological harm, or the concentration of
productive capacity in forms incompatible with commons governance is a
security imperative of equivalent standing to the control of nuclear weapons.
This principle shall inform American positions in all multilateral arms
control, disarmament, and export control forums.

(b) CONVENTIONAL ARMS EXPORT REVIEW.-- Within one year of the date of
enactment of this Act, the Secretary of State shall conduct a comprehensive
review of American conventional arms export policy, assessing each major
arms transfer program against the Nonproliferation Logic and identifying:

    (1) transfers whose primary effect is the reinforcement of extractive
    governance arrangements in recipient nations, the suppression of commons
    institution development, or the maintenance of authoritarian governments
    whose stability serves American resource access rather than genuine
    mutual security;

    (2) transfers to nations engaged in military operations whose primary
    purpose is the protection of fossil fuel infrastructure or the suppression
    of communities seeking to govern their own land and resources; and

    (3) transfers of surveillance technology, carceral infrastructure, and
    crowd control equipment whose deployment in recipient nations has
    documented effects incompatible with the commons values of this
    legislative program.

(c) ARMS EXPORT REFORM DIRECTIVE.-- On the basis of the review required by
subsection (b) of this Section, the Secretary of State shall:

    (1) terminate, within one year of the review's completion, all arms
    transfer programs identified as inconsistent with the Nonproliferation
    Logic;

    (2) establish as a condition of all future major arms transfer agreements
    a specific finding that the transfer serves a genuine mutual security
    purpose consistent with the Resilience-Based Defense Posture and does
    not primarily serve the protection of extractive arrangements or the
    suppression of commons institution development; and

    (3) report to Congress annually on the arms transfer programs terminated
    or modified pursuant to this Section, the diplomatic consequences of
    those terminations, and the alternative security assistance arrangements
    offered to affected partners.

(d) CARCERAL AND SURVEILLANCE TECHNOLOGY EXPORT PROHIBITION.-- Consistent
with Section 404(d) of the Human Reclamation and Community Restorative Act,
no federal agency shall provide funding, technical assistance, financing, or
export authorization for the transfer to any foreign government of:

    (1) predictive policing systems, mass surveillance infrastructure, or
    social scoring systems designed for deployment against civilian
    populations;

    (2) correctional facility design, management systems, or operational
    training whose purpose is the expansion of punitive incarceration
    capacity incompatible with the transformative justice principles of the
    Human Reclamation and Community Restorative Act; or

    (3) any technology whose primary application in the recipient nation is
    the identification, monitoring, or suppression of commons institution
    development, cooperative enterprise formation, or solidarity economy
    organizing.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 204. OVERSIGHT AND ACCOUNTABILITY.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) NUCLEAR POSTURE REVIEW SUBMISSION.-- The Nuclear Posture Review required
by Section 201(a)(3) of this Title shall be submitted to Congress in both
classified and unclassified form within one year of the date of enactment of
this Act, with the unclassified summary recorded on the National Resilience
Ledger as part of the commons governance history of this legislative program.

(b) ANNUAL NONPROLIFERATION REPORT.-- The Secretary of State shall submit to
Congress an annual Nonproliferation Report covering:

    (1) the status of NPT reengagement and bilateral arms control negotiations
    pursuant to Section 202 of this Title;

    (2) the status of conventional arms export review and reform pursuant to
    Section 203 of this Title;

    (3) an assessment of the consistency of American arms transfer activity
    during the preceding year with the Nonproliferation Logic; and

    (4) the specific arms transfer programs terminated or modified during the
    preceding year and the diplomatic and security consequences of those
    changes.

(c) INDEPENDENT REVIEW.-- The Arms Control and Disarmament Agency, if
reestablished, or the Government Accountability Office in the absence of such
an agency, shall conduct a biennial independent assessment of American
compliance with the Nonproliferation Logic as applied to arms control,
disarmament, and export control policy, reporting findings to Congress with
recommendations for corrective action.


================================================================================
TITLE III -- MULTILATERAL INSTITUTION REFORM
================================================================================

The purpose of this Title is to reorient American participation in the
International Monetary Fund, the World Bank Group, the World Trade
Organization, and related multilateral economic institutions toward positions
consistent with the commons values of this legislative program, and
specifically toward the elimination of Extractive Structural Conditions whose
imposition on developing nations has systematically prevented the development
of the cooperative institutions, community land trusts, commons intellectual
property frameworks, and federated governance structures that this legislative
program establishes domestically. A nation that commits, through the Federal
Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act, to removing land from
speculative markets, returning data and intellectual property to the commons,
and providing every community member with a Guaranteed Provision Standard
cannot coherently support, through its participation in multilateral
institutions, the imposition of conditions on other nations that prevent them
from doing the same. This Title closes that contradiction. It does not direct
the withdrawal of the United States from any multilateral institution; it
directs the use of American institutional influence toward the reform of those
institutions, and provides for American support of alternative frameworks where
reform proves unachievable within existing institutional structures.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 301. DECLARATION OF MULTILATERAL INSTITUTION POLICY.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) DECLARATION.-- It is hereby declared to be the policy of the United States
that its participation in all multilateral economic institutions shall be
governed by the following principles:

    (1) no multilateral institution in which the United States participates
    shall impose Extractive Structural Conditions, as defined in Section 4(3)
    of this Act, on any member nation as a condition of financing, debt relief,
    trade access, or technical assistance;

    (2) American representatives at all multilateral economic institutions
    shall advocate for development financing models that support commons
    institution development, cooperative enterprise formation, community land
    trust formation, and federated governance infrastructure in recipient
    nations, treating these as legitimate and preferable alternatives to
    privatization and market liberalization as development strategies;

    (3) American representatives at all multilateral economic institutions
    shall oppose any institutional position, policy, or condition that would
    prevent a member nation from establishing or maintaining the equivalent
    of a Guaranteed Provision Standard for its population, recognizing that
    the provision of housing, nutrition, healthcare, and knowledge access is
    a prerequisite for the genuine development that multilateral institutions
    exist to promote; and

    (4) American participation in multilateral trade institutions shall be
    directed toward the reform of intellectual property regimes that prevent
    developing nations from accessing essential medicines, agricultural
    technologies, and open-source technical designs on terms consistent with
    the Intellectual Property Commons established by the Federal Resilience
    and Decentralization Initiatives Act.

(b) EXECUTIVE DIRECTOR INSTRUCTIONS.-- The Secretary of the Treasury, with
respect to the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank Group, and the
United States Trade Representative, with respect to the World Trade
Organization, shall issue instructions to American Executive Directors and
representatives at those institutions directing compliance with the policy
declaration of subsection (a) of this Section within ninety days of the date
of enactment of this Act. Those instructions shall:

    (1) be specific and operational, identifying the categories of condition,
    position, and policy that American representatives shall oppose and the
    alternative positions they shall advocate;

    (2) be updated not less than annually to reflect the evolving
    implementation of this legislative program and the changing landscape
    of multilateral institution governance; and

    (3) be submitted to the congressional foreign affairs, financial services,
    and ways and means committees within thirty days of issuance, and recorded
    on the National Resilience Ledger as part of the commons governance history
    of this legislative program.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 302. STRUCTURAL ADJUSTMENT REFORM DIRECTIVES.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) MANDATORY ISSUANCE.-- The United States Executive Director at the
International Monetary Fund and the United States Executive Director at the
World Bank shall issue a Structural Adjustment Reform Directive, as defined
in Section 4(13) of this Act, with respect to any financing, debt relief, or
technical assistance arrangement that includes an Extractive Structural
Condition, within thirty days of that condition coming to the attention of the
relevant Executive Director through any means, including through the
institution's own documentation, reports by affected member nations, or
monitoring by civil society organizations.

(b) SCOPE.-- Structural Adjustment Reform Directives shall be issued with
respect to conditions imposed on any member nation, not only nations receiving
emergency financing, recognizing that Extractive Structural Conditions have
been embedded in routine program reviews, article consultations, and technical
assistance arrangements as well as in emergency lending.

(c) CONTENT.-- Each Structural Adjustment Reform Directive shall:

    (1) identify the specific condition, requirement, or policy prescription
    that constitutes an Extractive Structural Condition, with reference to
    the definition of Section 4(3) of this Act;

    (2) direct the institution to modify, withdraw, or refrain from imposing
    the identified condition within a defined timeline, not to exceed ninety
    days;

    (3) propose, where appropriate, an alternative condition or policy
    recommendation consistent with commons institution development in the
    affected member nation; and

    (4) be transmitted to the affected member nation's government with an
    explanation of the United States position, as an expression of commons
    solidarity rather than of unilateral American economic pressure.

(d) REPORTING.-- The Secretary of the Treasury shall report to Congress
quarterly on all Structural Adjustment Reform Directives issued during the
preceding quarter, the institutional response to each directive, and the
status of any condition identified as Extractive that has not yet been
modified or withdrawn.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 303. IMF REFORM AGENDA.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) QUOTA AND GOVERNANCE REFORM.-- The United States Executive Director at
the International Monetary Fund is directed to advocate for the following
governance reforms, reflecting the Nonproliferation Logic's application to
the international monetary system:

    (1) reallocation of IMF quota shares to better reflect the economic
    weight of developing nations, reducing the effective veto power of
    developed nations over program conditions affecting populations that bear
    the costs of those conditions most directly;

    (2) reform of the IMF's program conditionality framework to explicitly
    permit and support commons institution development, cooperative enterprise
    formation, and community land trust formation as legitimate development
    strategies, with conditionality focused on fiscal sustainability and
    governance transparency rather than on the specific economic arrangements
    through which those goals are pursued;

    (3) establishment of a Commons Development Financing Facility within the
    IMF, providing concessional financing specifically for the development of
    commons infrastructure in member nations, on terms equivalent to those
    available under the Stewardship Loan program of Section 306(b) of the
    Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act; and

    (4) reform of the IMF's debt sustainability framework to treat investment
    in commons infrastructure, renewable energy capacity, and cooperative food
    systems as productive public investment whose returns justify the associated
    financing, rather than as consumption expenditure to be minimized under
    fiscal consolidation conditions.

(b) SPECIAL DRAWING RIGHTS.-- The United States Executive Director is directed
to advocate for an allocation of Special Drawing Rights specifically designated
for commons infrastructure development in low-income member nations, building
on the precedent of the 2021 SDR allocation and directing it specifically
toward the seed capitalization of cooperative institutions, community land
trusts, and data commons governance infrastructure in nations seeking to
develop federated commons frameworks.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 304. WORLD BANK REFORM AGENDA.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) LENDING CRITERIA REFORM.-- The United States Executive Directors at the
International Bank for Reconstruction and Development, the International
Development Association, and all other components of the World Bank Group are
directed to advocate for the following reforms to World Bank lending criteria
and project design:

    (1) explicit recognition of cooperative enterprises, community land trusts,
    solidarity economy networks, and federated commons governance institutions
    as eligible project implementing entities for World Bank financing, on terms
    equivalent to those available to private sector and governmental
    implementing entities;

    (2) elimination of privatization conditions from all World Bank financing
    arrangements, consistent with the Structural Adjustment Reform Directive
    framework of Section 302 of this Title;

    (3) establishment of a Commons Infrastructure Lending Window providing
    project financing specifically for commons institution development,
    equivalent in scale to existing private sector lending windows and governed
    by a borrower advisory council with meaningful representation from commons
    institutions in recipient nations; and

    (4) reform of World Bank environmental and social safeguards to explicitly
    protect communities whose land, water, and ecological resources are affected
    by Bank-financed projects from displacement, enclosure, or the
    privatization of commons assets, with affected community consent required
    as a condition of project approval.

(b) KNOWLEDGE COMMONS CONTRIBUTION.-- The United States Executive Directors
are directed to advocate for the contribution of all World Bank research
outputs, development datasets, and technical assistance materials to a
publicly accessible knowledge commons, governed on principles equivalent to
the Intellectual Property Commons established by the Federal Resilience and
Decentralization Initiatives Act, freely accessible to all member nations and
to commons institutions worldwide without licensing fees or access
restrictions.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 305. WTO REFORM AGENDA.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) TRIPS REFORM.-- The United States Trade Representative is directed to
advocate for the following reforms to the Agreement on Trade-Related Aspects
of Intellectual Property Rights, consistent with the Nonproliferation Logic
applied to the international intellectual property system:

    (1) permanent extension of the TRIPS waiver for essential medicines to
    cover all health technologies whose access is necessary to maintain a
    provision standard equivalent to the Guaranteed Provision Standard,
    including vaccines, diagnostics, therapeutics, and medical devices;

    (2) establishment of a TRIPS commons exception permitting member nations
    to adopt intellectual property regimes equivalent to the Intellectual
    Property Commons of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization
    Initiatives Act, including shortened copyright terms, commons contribution
    of publicly funded research, and shelved patent recapture mechanisms,
    without those regimes being challengeable as TRIPS violations;

    (3) reform of TRIPS enforcement provisions to eliminate the use of trade
    sanctions against nations whose intellectual property regimes prioritize
    access to essential goods and knowledge over the protection of corporate
    IP monopolies; and

    (4) recognition of traditional knowledge, community innovations, and
    indigenous intellectual contributions as prior art in all WTO member
    nations' patent systems, consistent with the Traditional Knowledge Prior
    Art Database established under Section 404(e)(2) of the Federal Resilience
    and Decentralization Initiatives Act.

(b) AGRICULTURAL TRADE REFORM.-- The United States Trade Representative is
directed to advocate for reform of WTO agricultural trade rules to:

    (1) permit member nations to maintain food sovereignty measures, including
    import restrictions, price supports, and public procurement preferences
    for domestically produced food, where those measures are necessary to
    maintain the food commons provisions equivalent to Section 204 of the
    Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act;

    (2) eliminate agricultural subsidy disciplines that apply asymmetrically
    to developing nations, permitting developed nations to maintain production
    supports while prohibiting developing nations from equivalent measures
    necessary to seed cooperative agricultural enterprises; and

    (3) recognize the right of communities to save, share, and develop seeds
    and plant genetic resources as a fundamental component of food sovereignty,
    not subject to intellectual property claims by any party.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 306. ALTERNATIVE MULTILATERAL FRAMEWORKS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) FINDING.-- Congress finds that the reform agenda established by this Title
may not be achievable within the existing governance structures of the
International Monetary Fund, the World Bank, or the World Trade Organization
within the timeframes that the commons transition requires, given the voting
weight of nations with strong interests in maintaining Extractive Structural
Conditions and the institutional inertia of organizations whose operational
cultures have been shaped by decades of market liberalization orthodoxy. This
Section provides for American support of alternative multilateral frameworks
more consistent with commons values, not as a substitute for the reform agenda
of Sections 302 through 305 but as a parallel track ensuring that the commons
transition proceeds regardless of the pace of existing institutional reform.

(b) ALTERNATIVE FRAMEWORK SUPPORT.-- The Secretary of State is authorized to
negotiate and, subject to the advice and consent of the Senate where required
by the Constitution, conclude agreements with foreign governments and
international organizations providing for American participation in or support
of multilateral frameworks that:

    (1) provide development financing without Extractive Structural Conditions,
    on terms consistent with commons institution development in recipient
    nations;

    (2) govern international intellectual property relationships on terms
    consistent with the Intellectual Property Commons of the Federal Resilience
    and Decentralization Initiatives Act, including commons contribution of
    publicly funded research, shortened copyright terms, and traditional
    knowledge protection;

    (3) govern international trade relationships on terms consistent with food
    sovereignty, commons infrastructure protection, and the right of member
    nations to maintain provision standards equivalent to the Guaranteed
    Provision Standard; and

    (4) provide for the mutual recognition of commons institutions, federated
    networks, and Allied Commons Networks across national borders, consistent
    with the Commons Federation Agreement framework of Title IV of this Act.

(c) EXISTING ALTERNATIVE FRAMEWORKS.-- The Secretary of State shall, within
one year of the date of enactment of this Act, assess existing alternative
multilateral frameworks -- including regional development banks, South-South
cooperation arrangements, and bilateral commons federation agreements already
in operation -- for their consistency with the commons values of this
legislative program and their potential for American participation or support,
reporting findings to Congress with specific recommendations.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 307. DEBT RELIEF AND COMMONS TRANSITION.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) FINDING.-- Congress finds that the sovereign debt burdens of many
developing nations -- accumulated in part through borrowing at commercial rates
to finance development models whose conditions were imposed by the International
Monetary Fund and the World Bank -- constitute a structural barrier to commons
institution development as significant as any formal Extractive Structural
Condition. A nation whose fiscal capacity is consumed by debt service to
foreign creditors cannot invest in the cooperative infrastructure, community
land trusts, and knowledge commons that this legislative program establishes
domestically. Debt relief directed toward commons transition is therefore both
an act of commons solidarity and an application of the Nonproliferation Logic
to the international financial system.

(b) DEBT RELIEF DIRECTIVE.-- The Secretary of the Treasury is directed to:

    (1) advocate within the Paris Club, the G20 Common Framework, and all
    other multilateral debt restructuring forums for debt relief conditioned
    on commons institution development rather than on market liberalization,
    providing that debt service savings realized through relief shall be
    directed toward the establishment of cooperative enterprises, community
    land trusts, open-source commons, and federated governance infrastructure
    in the relieved nation;

    (2) support the establishment of a multilateral Commons Transition Debt
    Facility providing debt cancellation for nations that commit to commons
    development pathways, funded through contributions from creditor nations
    proportional to their historical role in imposing the Extractive Structural
    Conditions that contributed to the debt burden being relieved; and

    (3) oppose any debt restructuring arrangement that conditions relief on
    the privatization of public or commonly held assets, the reduction of
    social provision below the equivalent of the Guaranteed Provision Standard,
    or the adoption of intellectual property regimes incompatible with the
    Intellectual Property Commons of the Federal Resilience and
    Decentralization Initiatives Act.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 308. OVERSIGHT AND ACCOUNTABILITY.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) ANNUAL MULTILATERAL INSTITUTION REPORT.-- The Secretary of the Treasury
and the United States Trade Representative shall jointly submit to Congress
an annual Multilateral Institution Report covering:

    (1) all Structural Adjustment Reform Directives issued during the preceding
    year pursuant to Section 302 of this Title, the institutional response to
    each, and the status of identified Extractive Structural Conditions;

    (2) the status of IMF, World Bank, and WTO reform advocacy pursuant to
    Sections 303 through 305 of this Title, including the positions of other
    member nations and the prospects for achieving the reforms directed;

    (3) an assessment of the consistency of American multilateral institution
    participation during the preceding year with the policy declaration of
    Section 301 of this Title; and

    (4) the status of alternative multilateral framework negotiations and
    assessments pursuant to Section 306 of this Title.

(b) INDEPENDENT REVIEW.-- The Government Accountability Office shall conduct
a biennial independent review of American multilateral institution
participation, assessing compliance with this Title and reporting findings
to Congress with recommendations for corrective action.


================================================================================
TITLE IV -- INTERNATIONAL COMMONS FEDERATION
================================================================================

The purpose of this Title is to establish the legal architecture for a
planetary commons federation without center, without hierarchy, and without
the extraction dynamic that has defined every prior form of international
institutional integration. The commons federation this Title enables is the
structural inverse of empire: it seeds self-governing institutions at every
node of the network, connects them laterally through shared governance
principles and mutual provision obligations, and actively reverses the
extraction dynamic by returning to communities the productive capacity, the
knowledge commons, and the land stewardship that prior arrangements removed.
No node in this federation is subordinate to any other. The United States is
one federated network among many, distinguished by its current institutional
capacity but not by any claim to governance authority over any other node.
The Allied Commons Networks whose recognition this Title provides, and the
Commons Federation Agreements whose negotiation it authorizes, are the legal
instruments through which the planetary commons federation described in
Finding 16 of Section 3 of this Act becomes operative in international law.
This Title builds on the International Federation Framework established in
Section 1005 of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act,
extending and formalizing the framework that Act anticipated.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 401. ALLIED COMMONS NETWORK RECOGNITION.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) RECOGNITION AUTHORITY.-- The Secretary of State is hereby authorized to
formally recognize foreign commons institutions, federations of commons
institutions, and municipal commons governance bodies as Allied Commons
Networks, upon a determination that:

    (1) the institution, federation, or body operates under governance
    principles substantively equivalent to the Ostrom Standards of
    Stewardship, assessed through the criteria established in subsection
    (b) of this Section;

    (2) the institution, federation, or body has expressed a commitment to
    the commons values of this legislative program through its governance
    documents, operational history, or formal declaration; and

    (3) recognition would serve the commons solidarity purposes of this Title
    without creating obligations inconsistent with existing American treaty
    commitments or with the security provisions of Titles I and II of this
    Act.

(b) RECOGNITION CRITERIA.-- In assessing whether a foreign institution
operates under governance principles substantively equivalent to the Ostrom
Standards of Stewardship, the Secretary of State shall evaluate whether the
institution demonstrates, in its governance documents and operational practice,
functional equivalents of the following:

    (1) clearly defined boundaries of membership and shared resource scope;

    (2) governance rules adapted to local conditions rather than imposed from
    outside the community;

    (3) collective decision-making processes providing meaningful participation
    by affected members;

    (4) monitoring of shared resource health and governance compliance;

    (5) proportional responses to rule violations, oriented toward restoration
    rather than punishment;

    (6) accessible conflict resolution mechanisms;

    (7) recognized autonomy from external governmental interference in internal
    governance matters; and

    (8) nested governance architecture for coordination at appropriate scales.

    Full formal equivalence to each Standard as operationalized under the
    Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act is not required;
    the assessment is of substantive functional equivalence appropriate to
    the institution's legal, cultural, and institutional context.

(c) RECOGNITION PROCESS.-- Recognition of an Allied Commons Network shall
proceed as follows:

    (1) any foreign commons institution, group of institutions, or municipal
    commons governance body may apply for recognition through the United
    States Embassy or diplomatic mission in the relevant nation, or through
    the Office of Federated Stewardship's international liaison function
    established under subsection (e) of this Section;

    (2) the Secretary of State, in consultation with the Office of Federated
    Stewardship, shall complete the recognition assessment within one hundred
    eighty days of receipt of a complete application;

    (3) recognition shall be recorded on the National Resilience Ledger,
    making the Allied Commons Network's status visible to all certified
    Qualified Federated Networks and enabling direct network-to-network
    federation relationships to develop; and

    (4) recognition may be withdrawn upon a specific written finding by the
    Secretary of State that the recognized institution has materially departed
    from the governance principles on which recognition was based, with the
    institution provided notice and a one-hundred-eighty-day opportunity to
    demonstrate continued compliance before withdrawal takes effect.

(d) EXISTING INTERNATIONAL COMMONS NETWORKS.-- The following categories of
existing international commons institutions are hereby recognized as
presumptively eligible for Allied Commons Network status upon application,
reflecting their demonstrated alignment with commons governance principles:

    (1) member organizations of the International Center for Community Land
    Trusts and its affiliated regional networks;

    (2) cooperative enterprises affiliated with the International Cooperative
    Alliance operating under the ICA's cooperative principles, which are
    substantially equivalent to the Ostrom Standards in their governance
    requirements;

    (3) municipal commons governance bodies affiliated with the fearless
    cities network initiated by Barcelona en Comu;

    (4) solidarity economy networks affiliated with the Intercontinental
    Network for the Promotion of the Social Solidarity Economy; and

    (5) open-source commons communities and cooperative technology institutions
    whose governance and licensing practices are consistent with the
    Intellectual Property Commons of the Federal Resilience and
    Decentralization Initiatives Act.

(e) OFFICE OF FEDERATED STEWARDSHIP -- INTERNATIONAL LIAISON.-- The Office
of Federated Stewardship established under Section 107 of the Federal
Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act shall establish an
International Liaison function responsible for:

    (1) receiving and processing applications for Allied Commons Network
    recognition in coordination with the Secretary of State;

    (2) providing technical assistance to foreign commons institutions seeking
    recognition, including guidance on governance document adaptation and
    Ostrom Standards equivalence assessment;

    (3) maintaining the registry of recognized Allied Commons Networks on the
    National Resilience Ledger; and

    (4) facilitating direct network-to-network relationships between certified
    Qualified Federated Networks and recognized Allied Commons Networks,
    consistent with the Commons Federation Agreement framework of Section 402
    of this Title.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 402. COMMONS FEDERATION AGREEMENTS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) NEGOTIATING AUTHORITY.-- The Secretary of State is hereby authorized to
negotiate Commons Federation Agreements, as defined in Section 4(2) of this
Act, with foreign governments and recognized Allied Commons Networks. Commons
Federation Agreements shall be negotiated on the following principles:

    (1) SOVEREIGN EQUALITY.-- each party to a Commons Federation Agreement
    enters as a sovereign equal, with no party's governance preferences taking
    precedence over those of any other, and with the agreement's terms
    reflecting the genuine interests of all parties rather than the leverage
    of any single party;

    (2) VOLUNTARY FEDERATION.-- participation in any aspect of the Commons
    Federation Agreement framework is voluntary for all parties, with no
    party obligated to extend any provision beyond what it has specifically
    agreed to provide;

    (3) MUTUAL BENEFIT.-- Commons Federation Agreements shall be structured
    to provide genuine mutual benefit to all parties, with the specific terms
    of each agreement reflecting the particular commons development needs and
    capacities of the parties involved;

    (4) LATERAL GOVERNANCE.-- the governance of inter-network relationships
    under Commons Federation Agreements shall operate through the nested
    governance principles of Standard 8 of the Ostrom Standards of
    Stewardship, with decisions made at the lowest governance level capable
    of effectively addressing the matter at issue; and

    (5) NO CONDITIONALITY.-- Commons Federation Agreements shall not attach
    political, economic, or governance conditions to the provision of commons
    solidarity resources, technical assistance, or open-source technology
    transfer beyond the governance principles equivalence assessment of
    Section 401(b) of this Title.

(b) STANDARD PROVISIONS.-- Commons Federation Agreements shall provide, at
minimum, for the following, with each provision subject to the specific terms
negotiated with each party:

    (1) MUTUAL COMMONS MEMBERSHIP RECOGNITION.-- recognition of Federated
    Commons Membership held by individuals within the Federated Network as
    valid for access to equivalent provision standards within the Allied
    Commons Network's territory, and vice versa, on terms that respect the
    capacity constraints of each network and the portability principles of
    Section 210 of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives
    Act;

    (2) INTER-COMMONS INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY SHARING.-- mutual access to the
    Intellectual Property Commons of each party, under reciprocal copyleft
    obligations consistent with Section 507 of the Federal Resilience and
    Decentralization Initiatives Act, with traditional knowledge contributions
    governed by the Bounded Commons Contribution provisions of Section 404(c)
    of that Act;

    (3) INTER-COMMONS DATA GOVERNANCE.-- mutual privacy-compatible protocols
    for data exchange between the data commons of each party, under mutual
    privacy protection obligations consistent with Title IV of the Federal
    Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act;

    (4) COMMONS-TO-COMMONS RESOURCE EXCHANGE.-- frameworks for the exchange
    of surplus commons resources between the parties, at use value rates and
    under the provision priority rule of Section 307(d) of the Federal
    Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act, applied reciprocally;
    and

    (5) FEDERATED MESH INTEROPERABILITY.-- technical arrangements for
    Federated Mesh Open Standard compatibility between the network
    infrastructure of each party, enabling direct peer-to-peer resource
    coordination across national borders without dependence on any
    centralized intermediary.

(c) MULTILATERAL FEDERATION.-- Where three or more nations or Allied Commons
Networks seek to enter a Commons Federation Agreement, the Secretary of State
is authorized to negotiate a multilateral agreement providing for a regional
commons federation governed by the nested governance principles of the Ostrom
Standards, with the specific governance architecture determined by the parties
collectively. Regional commons federations established under this subsection
may develop their own governance institutions, provided those institutions
operate on principles consistent with this Act and do not claim governance
authority over any party beyond what that party has specifically agreed to
grant.

(d) SUBMISSION TO CONGRESS.-- Commons Federation Agreements shall be submitted
to Congress for review pursuant to the Case-Zablocki Act and, where their
provisions constitute treaty obligations requiring Senate advice and consent
under Article II, Section 2 of the Constitution, shall be submitted to the
Senate accordingly. The determination of whether a Commons Federation Agreement
requires Senate advice and consent shall be made by the Secretary of State in
consultation with the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, with a presumption
in favor of Senate submission for agreements establishing significant new mutual
provision obligations.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 403. INTERNATIONAL COMMONS SOLIDARITY FUND.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) ESTABLISHMENT.-- There is hereby established the International Commons
Solidarity Fund, as defined in Section 4(5) of this Act, to provide technical
assistance, open-source technology transfer, commons governance capacity-
building support, and seed capitalization to commons institutions in nations
seeking to develop federated commons infrastructure. The International Commons
Solidarity Fund is the primary instrument through which the planetary commons
federation described in Finding 16 of Section 3 of this Act is materially
resourced, and its operation shall reflect the principles of that Finding: no
conditionality beyond governance equivalence, no hierarchy between donor and
recipient, no extraction of political compliance in exchange for commons
solidarity.

(b) FUNDING.-- The International Commons Solidarity Fund shall be funded
through:

    (1) the mechanisms established in Section 1005(e) of the Federal
    Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act, providing that a defined
    percentage of the surplus generated by external resource trade within the
    Federated Network flows to the Fund;

    (2) the nuclear force reduction savings redirected pursuant to Section
    201(a)(4) of Title II of this Act;

    (3) the defense posture transition savings redirected pursuant to Section
    103(b)(3) of the Federal Commons Security and Automation Governance Act,
    to the extent those savings are designated for the International Commons
    Solidarity Fund; and

    (4) such appropriations as Congress may provide pursuant to Section 502
    of Title V of this Act.

(c) ELIGIBLE ACTIVITIES.-- The International Commons Solidarity Fund shall
provide support for the following categories of activity in nations with
recognized Allied Commons Networks or with commons institutions in the process
of seeking recognition:

    (1) GOVERNANCE CAPACITY BUILDING.-- training, facilitation, and technical
    assistance for commons institution governance, including Ostrom Standards
    equivalence assessment, collective decision-making process design, conflict
    resolution infrastructure, and peer monitoring system development;

    (2) OPEN-SOURCE TECHNOLOGY TRANSFER.-- provision of Federated Mesh Open
    Standard compatible hardware, open-source software tools, and technical
    training for commons infrastructure deployment, including the Analytics
    Commons tools of the Federal Commons Security and Automation Governance
    Act and the Decidim-DAO governance bridge;

    (3) SEED CAPITALIZATION.-- grant funding for the formation of cooperative
    enterprises, community land trusts, data commons, and knowledge commons
    institutions, on terms equivalent to the Bootstrap Grant Program of
    Section 106 of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives
    Act, adapted to the legal and economic contexts of recipient nations;

    (4) LEGAL AND INSTITUTIONAL ASSISTANCE.-- support for the development of
    national legal frameworks enabling commons institution formation, federated
    network certification, and commons asset protection in recipient nations,
    including model legislation, legal training, and technical drafting
    assistance; and

    (5) INTER-NETWORK CONNECTION.-- technical and governance assistance for
    establishing Federated Mesh interoperability between nascent commons
    networks in recipient nations and existing Qualified Federated Networks
    and Allied Commons Networks, enabling the lateral federation relationships
    through which the planetary commons network grows.

(d) GOVERNANCE.-- The International Commons Solidarity Fund shall be governed
by a board comprising:

    (1) not fewer than five representatives of certified Qualified Federated
    Networks within the United States, selected through the governance
    processes of the Federated Network;

    (2) not fewer than five representatives of recognized Allied Commons
    Networks, selected through the governance processes of those networks,
    with geographic representation across at least three continents;

    (3) not fewer than three representatives of commons institutions in nations
    that have applied for but not yet received Allied Commons Network
    recognition, selected through a process determined by the Office of
    Federated Stewardship's International Liaison function in consultation
    with international commons organization networks;

    (4) one representative nominated by RIPESS (Intercontinental Network for
    the Promotion of Social Solidarity Economy), as the primary existing global
    solidarity economy coordinating body whose member networks are the principal
    beneficiary constituency of the Fund, selected through RIPESS's own
    governance processes; this seat shall be a voting seat, with the RIPESS
    nominee counted toward the Allied Commons Network representation of
    paragraph (2) of this subsection where the nominee is affiliated with a
    recognized Allied Commons Network, and counted as an additional seat where
    the nominee represents a network not yet recognized;

    (5) one representative nominated by the International Center for Community
    Land Trusts (ICCLT), as the primary existing global CLT network coordinator,
    selected through ICCLT's own governance processes and counted on the same
    terms as the RIPESS seat in paragraph (4) of this subsection;

    (6) a non-voting liaison from the Office of Federated Stewardship; and

    (7) a non-voting liaison from the Department of State.

(e) NO CONDITIONALITY.-- The International Commons Solidarity Fund shall not
attach political, economic, military, or governance conditions to the provision
of any support beyond the governance equivalence principles of Section 401(b)
of this Title. Specifically:

    (1) Fund support shall not be conditioned on a recipient nation's positions
    in any bilateral or multilateral negotiation with the United States;

    (2) Fund support shall not be conditioned on a recipient institution's
    adoption of any specific economic arrangement beyond the commons governance
    principles that define eligibility; and

    (3) Fund support shall not be used as leverage in any diplomatic, trade,
    or security relationship between the United States and any recipient nation.

(f) ACCOUNTABILITY.-- The International Commons Solidarity Fund board shall
submit an annual report to Congress and to the Federated Network membership,
recorded on the National Resilience Ledger, covering the Fund's activities,
expenditures, and outcomes during the preceding year, assessed against the
commons development goals of recipient institutions rather than against metrics
imposed by the Fund itself.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 404. COMMONS FOREIGN ASSISTANCE REORIENTATION.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) FINDING.-- Congress finds that the existing architecture of American
foreign assistance -- organized around USAID programs, bilateral military
assistance, and multilateral development institution contributions -- has been
designed primarily to serve American geopolitical and commercial interests
rather than the genuine development needs of recipient communities. This
Section does not abolish American foreign assistance; it reorients it toward
commons institution development, treating the seed capitalization of
cooperative enterprises, community land trusts, and federated commons
governance infrastructure as the primary expression of American solidarity
with peoples seeking to govern their own material lives.

(b) USAID REORIENTATION.-- The Administrator of the United States Agency for
International Development shall, within one year of the date of enactment of
this Act, reorient USAID programming to:

    (1) designate commons institution development -- including cooperative
    enterprise formation, community land trust development, data commons
    governance, and knowledge commons infrastructure -- as a primary
    programming priority equivalent in standing to existing USAID priorities
    in democracy, health, and economic growth;

    (2) establish a Commons Development Office within USAID responsible for
    coordinating commons institution development programming, working in
    direct partnership with the Office of Federated Stewardship's
    International Liaison function and the International Commons Solidarity
    Fund board;

    (3) eliminate programming conditions that require recipient organizations
    to adopt market liberalization, privatization, or intellectual property
    arrangements inconsistent with commons institution development, consistent
    with the prohibition on Extractive Structural Conditions of Title III of
    this Act; and

    (4) prioritize direct partnerships with Allied Commons Networks and commons
    institution applicants in recipient nations over partnerships with national
    governments or international NGOs whose programming models are inconsistent
    with the commons governance principles of this legislative program.

(c) MILITARY ASSISTANCE REORIENTATION.-- The Secretary of Defense and the
Secretary of State shall jointly review all military assistance and security
cooperation programs within one year of the date of enactment of this Act,
and shall terminate or modify any program whose primary effect is:

    (1) the reinforcement of governing arrangements that suppress commons
    institution development, cooperative enterprise formation, or community
    land stewardship in recipient nations;

    (2) the provision of capabilities used primarily for the protection of
    extractive resource interests rather than for the genuine security of the
    recipient nation's population; or

    (3) the transfer of surveillance, carceral, or crowd control capabilities
    prohibited under Section 203(d) of Title II of this Act.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 405. PLANETARY COMMONS FEDERATION -- LONG-TERM VISION.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) DECLARATION.-- It is hereby declared to be the long-term vision of the
United States, encoded in the legal architecture of this Act, that the
international order toward which this legislative program is oriented is one
in which:

    (1) every community on earth has access to the material conditions of a
    dignified life through self-governing commons institutions federated
    laterally with their neighbors, without dependence on the charity of
    wealthier nations or the conditionality of international financial
    institutions;

    (2) the knowledge, creative expression, and technical innovation of all
    peoples flows freely through a planetary intellectual property commons,
    permanently attributed to its creators and permanently protected from
    enclosure by any party;

    (3) the ecological systems on which all human life depends are governed
    as global commons through institutions applying the Ostrom Standards at
    planetary scale, with no nation, corporation, or other actor permitted
    to treat the atmosphere, the oceans, the hydrological cycle, or the
    genetic diversity of life as a private resource to be exploited for
    extractive gain; and

    (4) the military and nuclear capabilities of all nations are calibrated
    to the minimum necessary for genuine collective defense, with the
    resources freed by their reduction redirected to the commons
    infrastructure whose material abundance makes the conflicts over scarcity
    that militarism has historically managed progressively unnecessary.

(b) PROGRESSIVE REALIZATION.-- Congress finds that the vision declared in
subsection (a) of this Section is not achievable through any single legislative
act or within any single political generation. It is achievable through the
progressive accumulation of commons institutions, the lateral federation of
those institutions across national borders, and the demonstrated material
adequacy that commons governance produces in the communities that adopt it.
The provisions of this Act are one step in that progressive realization.
Accordingly:

    (1) each five-year review conducted pursuant to subsection (c) of this
    Section shall include an assessment of whether additional legislative
    vehicles are warranted to advance the planetary commons federation, with
    specific recommendations for such vehicles submitted to Congress as part
    of the review report; and

    (2) the review required by subsection (c) of this Section shall be conducted
    with the meaningful participation of recognized Allied Commons Networks,
    whose assessments of their own progress and needs shall be solicited through
    the governance processes of the International Commons Solidarity Fund board
    established under Section 403(d) of this Title and shall be included in the
    review report submitted to Congress.

(c) REVIEW AND ADAPTATION.-- The Secretary of State shall submit to Congress,
every five years following the date of enactment of this Act, a comprehensive
review of the progress of the planetary commons federation established by this
Title, assessing:

    (1) the number and geographic distribution of recognized Allied Commons
    Networks and the provisions they deliver to their members;

    (2) the scope and depth of Commons Federation Agreements in force and the
    resource exchanges and knowledge sharing they have enabled;

    (3) the commons institution development outcomes achieved through the
    International Commons Solidarity Fund and USAID reorientation;

    (4) the progress of multilateral institution reform under Title III of this
    Act and its effects on commons institution development in member nations;
    and

    (5) recommendations for legislative and administrative adaptations to
    accelerate the planetary commons transition in light of what has been
    learned since the preceding review.


================================================================================
TITLE V -- ADMINISTRATIVE AND JUDICIAL PROVISIONS
================================================================================

The purpose of this Title is to establish the administrative framework,
judicial review mechanisms, dependency provisions, anti-capture protections,
conforming amendments, and appropriations authorities necessary to make the
preceding Titles operative and durable. This Title addresses directly the
predictable institutional responses to a legislative program of this scope
and ambition: the Executive Branch's tendency to reinterpret statutory
mandates in ways that restore the postures Congress has directed it to change;
the defense and foreign policy establishment's tendency to treat security
justifications as self-executing exemptions from statutory requirements; the
Military Industrial Complex's tendency to use its geographic distribution of
economic interests to generate congressional resistance to any provision that
reduces the scale or scope of defense contracting; and the revolving door
between governmental and private defense, intelligence, and financial sector
employment that has consistently produced regulatory capture of the
institutions Congress creates to govern those sectors. Each of these
tendencies is directly addressed in this Title. The armor plating is not
decorative; it is load-bearing.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 501. DEPENDENCY ON THE FRDI ACT, HRCR ACT, AND FCSAG.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) STRUCTURAL DEPENDENCY.-- The alliance governance, nuclear nonproliferation,
multilateral institution reform, and international commons federation provisions
of this Act are structurally dependent upon the domestic commons infrastructure
established by the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act,
the Human Reclamation and Community Restorative Act, and the Federal Commons
Security and Automation Governance Act. Specifically:

    (1) the NATO Resilience Framework negotiation directed by Title I of this
    Act is strategically credible only as the domestic commons infrastructure
    of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act matures,
    demonstrating that resilience-based security is a genuine alternative to
    petrodollar-dependent military projection rather than a theoretical
    aspiration;

    (2) the Nonproliferation Logic of Title II of this Act is operationally
    coherent only as the domestic energy transition enabled by the Federal
    Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act reduces American fossil
    fuel dependence, removing the strategic rationale for the military
    commitments whose reduction the Nonproliferation Logic directs;

    (3) the Structural Adjustment Reform Directives of Title III of this Act
    are diplomatically sustainable only when the United States can demonstrate,
    through the domestic commons transition, that the commons development
    models it advocates for other nations work in practice rather than in
    theory; and

    (4) the Allied Commons Network recognition and Commons Federation
    Agreements of Title IV of this Act are most credibly negotiated by a
    nation whose own federated commons networks are functioning, whose Commons
    Solidarity Fund contributions derive from the genuine surplus of a maturing
    commons economy, and whose International Liaison function within the Office
    of Federated Stewardship has the institutional knowledge that comes from
    governing a domestic commons transition.

(b) SEQUENCING.-- The following provisions of this Act shall not take operative
effect until the specified conditions are met:

    (1) the NATO Resilience Framework negotiating directive of Section 102 of
    Title I shall be initiated immediately upon enactment, but the United
    States shall not propose burden-sharing assessments crediting commons
    infrastructure investment until at least twenty-five Qualified Federated
    Networks have achieved certification pursuant to the Federal Resilience
    and Decentralization Initiatives Act, providing a demonstrable domestic
    basis for the resilience-based security model being proposed;

    (2) the International Commons Solidarity Fund of Section 403 of Title IV
    shall not begin disbursements funded through the commons surplus mechanism
    of Section 403(b)(1) of this Act until the Federated Network has achieved
    the network maturity threshold established in Section 107(f) of the Federal
    Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act, ensuring that solidarity
    fund contributions do not impair the domestic commons transition they are
    intended to model; and

    (3) the Allied Commons Network recognition process of Section 401 of Title
    IV shall be available immediately upon enactment, with the Office of
    Federated Stewardship's International Liaison function established within
    one year of the domestic Office's establishment pursuant to Section 107 of
    the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act.

(c) FEDERAL BACKSTOP.-- Where sequencing conditions have not yet been met in
a specific domain, the federal government shall:

    (1) continue fulfilling all existing treaty obligations in full during the
    period preceding the conditions for their renegotiation being met;

    (2) fund the International Commons Solidarity Fund through the
    appropriations of Section 502 of this Title during the period preceding
    the commons surplus mechanism becoming operative; and

    (3) staff the Office of Federated Stewardship's International Liaison
    function through the Department of State's existing foreign assistance
    and development cooperation infrastructure during the period preceding
    the Office's independent capacity being established.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 502. ANTI-CAPTURE PROVISIONS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) FINDING.-- Congress finds that the Military Industrial Complex's response
to this legislative program will operate on multiple fronts simultaneously:
through the legislative relationships generated by the geographic distribution
of defense contracting across congressional districts; through legal challenges
to force structure transition, intelligence reform, and analytics platform
commons capture; through the narrative framing of resilience-based defense as
weakness or abandonment; and through the revolving door between governmental
and private defense, intelligence, and financial sector employment that has
consistently produced regulatory capture of the institutions Congress creates
to govern those sectors. The provisions of this Section are designed to address
each of these vectors directly, providing the institutional armor plating
without which the preceding Titles cannot survive contact with the concentrated
interests they displace.

(b) CONFLICT OF INTEREST PROHIBITIONS -- GOVERNANCE BODIES.-- No person shall
serve on any governance body established by this Act, including the board of
the International Commons Solidarity Fund, the advisory bodies established
under Section 102 of Title I, the Nuclear Posture Review panel, or any other
body with decision-making authority over the provisions of this Act, if that
person:

    (1) is a current employee, officer, director, or significant shareholder
    of any defense contractor, intelligence community contractor, private
    equity fund with defense industry investments, or financial institution
    whose primary business involves the monetary arrangements this Act is
    designed to transition away from;

    (2) has been employed by any such entity within the five years preceding
    their appointment; or

    (3) has a financial interest in any contract, procurement, or commercial
    arrangement that would be materially affected by the decisions of the body
    on which they serve.

(c) POST-SERVICE RESTRICTIONS.-- Any person who serves on any governance body
established by this Act, or who serves as a senior official with implementation
responsibility for any provision of this Act, shall not, for a period of five
years following the conclusion of their service:

    (1) accept employment with any defense contractor, intelligence community
    contractor, or private equity fund with defense industry investments whose
    interests were materially affected by decisions made during their service;

    (2) represent any foreign government, international financial institution,
    or multilateral organization in any matter affecting the implementation of
    this Act; or

    (3) receive compensation from any entity that received a material benefit
    from any decision made during their service, in exchange for advice,
    advocacy, or other services related to the subject matter of that decision.

(d) GEOGRAPHIC DISTRIBUTION ANTI-CAPTURE.-- Congress finds that the geographic
distribution of defense contracting across congressional districts has
historically been used as a mechanism for generating legislative resistance to
force structure reductions, base closures, and procurement cancellations by
creating constituency employment dependencies that make cost-benefit assessment
politically impossible. The provisions of this Act address this directly by:

    (1) requiring that the defense savings redirected pursuant to Title I of
    the Federal Commons Security and Automation Governance Act and this Act
    be allocated preferentially to the communities most affected by force
    structure reductions, through the Bootstrap Grant Program and the
    International Commons Solidarity Fund, ensuring that the economic
    transition from defense dependence to commons economy occurs in the same
    communities where defense employment is reduced;

    (2) directing the Secretary of Defense, in the force structure transition
    reporting required by Section 103(e) of the Federal Commons Security and
    Automation Governance Act, to include a specific community economic
    transition plan for each base closure or significant force reduction,
    identifying the commons infrastructure investment, cooperative enterprise
    development, and Bootstrap Grant allocation directed to the affected
    community; and

    (3) establishing a Defense Community Transition Office within the
    Department of Defense, staffed by personnel with expertise in cooperative
    enterprise development and commons infrastructure, whose function is to
    ensure that no community experiences net economic harm from the force
    structure transition without receiving equivalent or greater investment
    through the commons economy mechanisms of this legislative program.

(e) LEGAL CHALLENGE ANTICIPATION.-- The following provisions address the
specific legal challenges most likely to be brought against this Act:

    (1) TAKINGS CHALLENGES.-- the commons capture of Intelligence-Community-
    Funded Analytics Platforms pursuant to Section 302 of Title III of the
    Federal Commons Security and Automation Governance Act is grounded in the
    public funding basis of the captured intellectual property, not in any
    general authority to take private property. The audit required by that
    Section specifically identifies the publicly funded components subject to
    capture, and compensation through Legacy Credits is provided for any
    privately funded value that is incidentally captured. Any takings claim
    arising from this provision shall be adjudicated on the basis of the
    specific proportion of publicly funded to privately funded intellectual
    property in the captured components, with the federal government bearing
    the burden of demonstrating the public funding basis and the platform
    holder bearing the burden of demonstrating any privately funded value
    subject to compensation;

    (2) CONTRACT CHALLENGES.-- existing contracts for defense services,
    intelligence community analytics, and foreign assistance programming that
    are inconsistent with this Act shall be honored through their current term
    and shall not be renewed on inconsistent terms. No provision of this Act
    shall be construed to abrogate any existing contract unilaterally; the Act
    operates on the contracting cycle, not against it; and

    (3) SEPARATION OF POWERS CHALLENGES.-- the directives issued to the
    President, the Secretary of State, the Secretary of Defense, and other
    executive officials throughout this Act are statutory mandates enacted
    pursuant to Congress's plenary authority over foreign affairs, defense
    appropriations, and treaty implementation. They do not unconstitutionally
    infringe executive power; they exercise Congress's constitutional authority
    to define the purposes for which defense and foreign affairs appropriations
    may be used and the conditions under which treaty obligations may be
    modified.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 503. EXECUTIVE BRANCH COMPLIANCE MECHANISMS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) NON-REINTERPRETATION PROVISION.-- The alliance governance policy
declaration of Section 101 of Title I of this Act, the Minimum Credible
Deterrence declaration of Section 201 of Title II, the multilateral institution
policy declaration of Section 301 of Title III, and the no-conditionality
requirement of Section 403(e) of Title IV are statutory directives to the
Executive Branch, not grants of discretion to the Executive Branch to determine
what those provisions mean. No executive order, presidential directive,
national security memorandum, or administrative guidance shall be issued that
reinterprets any of these provisions in a manner that restores the postures,
commitments, or conditions those provisions are designed to replace. Any such
executive reinterpretation shall be subject to immediate judicial review under
the standard established in subsection (b) of this Section upon the application
of any member of Congress, any certified Qualified Federated Network, or any
recognized Allied Commons Network.

(b) JUDICIAL REVIEW STANDARD.-- In any proceeding challenging executive action
under this Act:

    (1) the court shall apply de novo review without deference to the
    executive's interpretation of any policy declaration, mandate, or
    prohibition established by this Act;

    (2) any executive action asserting a national security justification for
    conduct otherwise prohibited by this Act shall be subject to searching
    judicial scrutiny rather than traditional deference, on the grounds that
    this Act itself constitutes a congressional determination of what genuine
    national security requires; and

    (3) the burden of demonstrating that any challenged action falls within
    the authority conferred by this Act shall rest with the Executive Branch.

(c) NATIONAL SECURITY EXCEPTION -- NARROW CONSTRUCTION.-- Any provision of
this Act that permits executive action upon a national security finding shall
be construed narrowly, with:

    (1) the finding required to be specific, written, and transmitted to the
    congressional foreign affairs and armed services committees within
    forty-eight hours of the action it justifies;

    (2) the finding subject to classified briefing to those committees within
    seven days; and

    (3) the action justified by the finding subject to termination if the
    committees jointly determine, within thirty days, that the national
    security justification is not supported by the evidence presented.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 504. CONSTITUTIONAL SAFE HARBOR.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Any federal officer, employee, or agent who in good faith takes any action to
implement the provisions of this Act -- including actions that result in the
renegotiation of alliance commitments, the reduction of nuclear force structure,
the issuance of Structural Adjustment Reform Directives, the recognition of
Allied Commons Networks, the commons capture of Intelligence-Community-Funded
Analytics Platforms, or the reorientation of foreign assistance toward commons
institution development -- shall not be subject to civil or criminal liability
under any federal or state law arising solely from the performance of those
implementation duties, on terms equivalent to the Constitutional Safe Harbor
established under Section 1101 of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization
Initiatives Act. This safe harbor is retroactive to the date of introduction
of this Act in Congress.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 505. SEVERABILITY.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) GENERAL SEVERABILITY.-- If any provision of this Act, or the application
of any provision to any person or circumstance, is held invalid by a court of
competent jurisdiction, the remainder of this Act and the application of its
provisions to other persons or circumstances shall not be affected.

(b) TITLE-LEVEL SEVERABILITY.-- Each Title of this Act is independently
operative and shall remain in full force and effect if any other Title or any
provision thereof is held invalid. In particular:

    (1) the invalidity of any provision of Title I concerning alliance
    governance shall not affect the operative force of Titles II, III, or IV;

    (2) the invalidity of any provision of Title II concerning nuclear
    nonproliferation shall not affect the alliance governance provisions of
    Title I or the international commons federation provisions of Title IV;
    and

    (3) the invalidity of the Structural Adjustment Reform Directive mechanism
    of Section 302 of Title III shall not affect the WTO and World Bank reform
    advocacy provisions of Sections 304 and 305 of that Title, which are
    independently operative.

(c) PROGRAM SEVERABILITY.-- The invalidity of any provision of this Act shall
not affect the operative force of any provision of the Federal Resilience and
Decentralization Initiatives Act, the Human Reclamation and Community
Restorative Act, or the Federal Commons Security and Automation Governance Act.
Each Act in this legislative program is independently operative and mutually
reinforcing; the invalidity of any provision in any Act affects only that
provision and not the broader program.

