SEC. 506. CONFORMING AMENDMENTS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) FOREIGN ASSISTANCE ACT.-- The Foreign Assistance Act of 1961, codified at
22 U.S.C. section 2151 et seq., is hereby amended to:

    (1) add commons institution development -- including cooperative enterprise
    formation, community land trust development, data commons governance, and
    knowledge commons infrastructure -- as an explicit development objective
    of American foreign assistance, equivalent in standing to existing
    objectives in democracy, economic growth, and humanitarian assistance;

    (2) prohibit the attachment of privatization conditions, intellectual
    property extension conditions, or capital account liberalization conditions
    to any American foreign assistance, consistent with the Extractive
    Structural Condition prohibition of Title III of this Act; and

    (3) authorize the Administrator of USAID to enter into direct partnership
    agreements with recognized Allied Commons Networks pursuant to Section 404
    of Title IV of this Act.

(b) ARMS EXPORT CONTROL ACT.-- The Arms Export Control Act, codified at 22
U.S.C. section 2751 et seq., is hereby amended to:

    (1) add the Nonproliferation Logic of Section 4(9) of this Act as a
    required consideration in all arms transfer determinations, alongside
    existing human rights and regional stability considerations;

    (2) prohibit the export of predictive policing systems, mass surveillance
    infrastructure, and carceral technology consistent with Section 203(d) of
    Title II of this Act; and

    (3) require a specific finding of consistency with the Nonproliferation
    Logic for any major arms transfer to a nation whose primary strategic
    significance to the United States derives from fossil fuel reserves rather
    than from a genuine mutual security relationship.

(c) BRETTON WOODS AGREEMENTS ACT.-- The Bretton Woods Agreements Act, codified
at 22 U.S.C. section 286 et seq., is hereby amended to direct the United States
Executive Director at the International Monetary Fund to issue Structural
Adjustment Reform Directives pursuant to Section 302 of Title III of this Act
as a mandatory duty, not subject to executive discretion, upon identification
of any Extractive Structural Condition in any IMF program or arrangement.

(d) INTERNATIONAL FINANCIAL INSTITUTIONS ACT.-- The International Financial
Institutions Act, codified at 22 U.S.C. section 262c et seq., is hereby amended
to:

    (1) add the elimination of Extractive Structural Conditions as an explicit
    American policy objective at all international financial institutions,
    incorporated into the instructions issued to American Executive Directors
    pursuant to Section 301(b) of Title III of this Act; and

    (2) require the Secretary of the Treasury to report to Congress annually
    on all Extractive Structural Conditions identified in World Bank programs
    and the Structural Adjustment Reform Directives issued in response.

(e) ATOMIC ENERGY ACT.-- The Atomic Energy Act of 1954, codified at 42 U.S.C.
section 2011 et seq., is hereby amended to incorporate the Minimum Credible
Deterrence standard of Section 201 of Title II of this Act as a governing
principle for nuclear weapons program authorization, requiring that all nuclear
weapons programs be justified against the Minimum Credible Deterrence standard
in the annual budget submission.

(f) CASE-ZABLOCKI ACT.-- The Case-Zablocki Act, codified at 1 U.S.C. section
112b, is hereby amended to require that Commons Federation Agreements negotiated
pursuant to Section 402 of Title IV of this Act be submitted to Congress
pursuant to the reporting requirements of that Act within sixty days of
signature, with a specific assessment of whether the agreement constitutes a
treaty requiring Senate advice and consent.

(g) NATIONAL SECURITY ACT OF 1947.-- The National Security Act of 1947,
codified at 50 U.S.C. section 3001 et seq., is hereby amended to require that
the annual National Security Strategy submitted to Congress pursuant to 50
U.S.C. section 3043 include a specific assessment of the consistency of
American national security policy with the Resilience-Based Defense Posture
and the Nonproliferation Logic of this Act, with any inconsistencies identified
and explained.

