SEC. 507. AUTHORIZATION OF APPROPRIATIONS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) GENERAL AUTHORIZATION.-- There are authorized to be appropriated to carry
out the purposes of this Act such sums as may be necessary for each fiscal year
following the date of enactment of this Act, subject to the specific
authorizations established in this Section.

(b) INTERNATIONAL COMMONS SOLIDARITY FUND.-- There are authorized to be
appropriated to the International Commons Solidarity Fund established under
Section 403 of Title IV of this Act:

    (1) not less than five hundred million dollars for the first fiscal year
    following enactment, for the establishment of the Fund's governance
    structure, the initial recognition of Allied Commons Networks, and the
    first round of seed capitalization grants;

    (2) not less than one billion dollars for each of the second through fifth
    fiscal years following enactment, expanding the Fund's operations to the
    full range of eligible activities established in Section 403(c) of Title
    IV of this Act; and

    (3) such sums as may be necessary for subsequent fiscal years, with the
    expectation that Fund contributions from the commons surplus mechanism of
    Section 403(b)(1) of this Act will progressively reduce dependence on
    congressional appropriations as the domestic commons economy matures.

(c) NATO RESILIENCE FRAMEWORK NEGOTIATION.-- There are authorized to be
appropriated for the diplomatic, technical, and analytical costs of NATO
Resilience Framework negotiations pursuant to Section 102 of Title I of this
Act not less than fifty million dollars for each of the first five fiscal years
following enactment, covering personnel, analysis, and the development of
resilience-based burden-sharing assessment methodologies.

(d) ALLIED COMMONS NETWORK RECOGNITION AND COMMONS FEDERATION AGREEMENTS.--
There are authorized to be appropriated for the recognition process, technical
assistance, and agreement negotiation functions established under Sections 401
and 402 of Title IV of this Act:

    (1) not less than one hundred million dollars for the first fiscal year
    following enactment, for the establishment of the Office of Federated
    Stewardship's International Liaison function and the initial recognition
    assessments; and

    (2) not less than seventy-five million dollars for each subsequent fiscal
    year for ongoing recognition, technical assistance, and agreement
    negotiation operations.

(e) USAID REORIENTATION.-- There are authorized to be appropriated for the
USAID Commons Development Office established under Section 404(b)(2) of Title
IV of this Act and the initial reorientation of USAID programming:

    (1) not less than two hundred fifty million dollars for the first fiscal
    year following enactment; and

    (2) not less than two hundred million dollars for each of the second
    through fifth fiscal years following enactment, with the expectation that
    the reoriented programming replaces rather than supplements existing USAID
    expenditure in comparable development areas.

(f) DEFENSE COMMUNITY TRANSITION OFFICE.-- There are authorized to be
appropriated for the Defense Community Transition Office established under
Section 502(d)(3) of this Title:

    (1) not less than one hundred million dollars for the first fiscal year
    following enactment; and

    (2) not less than one hundred fifty million dollars for each of the second
    through tenth fiscal years following enactment, reflecting the scale of
    community transition support required during the force structure transition
    period.

(g) MULTILATERAL INSTITUTION REFORM.-- There are authorized to be appropriated
for the analytical, diplomatic, and technical costs of the multilateral
institution reform agenda of Title III of this Act, including the development
of alternative multilateral framework proposals and the Commons Transition Debt
Facility:

    (1) not less than one hundred million dollars for the first fiscal year
    following enactment; and

    (2) not less than seventy-five million dollars for each subsequent fiscal
    year.

(h) FUNDING PRINCIPLES.-- The appropriations authorized by this Section reflect
the same front-loaded transition investment logic of the broader legislative
program: the costs of alliance renegotiation, nuclear posture review,
multilateral institution reform, and international commons federation
establishment are transitional investments whose long-term fiscal returns are
measured in reduced defense expenditure, reduced intelligence community
maintenance costs, reduced foreign assistance expenditure on programs whose
development outcomes have been poor, and the growing contribution of a maturing
global commons economy to the material security of people everywhere. The
Congressional Budget Office is directed to account for these long-term returns
in scoring the fiscal impact of this Act.

